Easy relax yoga. This style of yoga is called Yin, bringing a more relaxed, slow pace to the activity.

The poses help with reducing:- 

Lower Back Pain

Sciatic pain

Hip pain

Blood pressure 

Headaches

Stress 

Anxiety 

Also very beneficial to those who do sport or other high intensity exercise to help improve performance and reduce injury.

Caption:
WINNING ü•á!
Every single day I try and get a ‚ÄúWIN‚Äù.
How I measure my ‚ÄúW‚Äôs‚Äù may sound a little easy, but when you start stacking them ‚ÄúW‚Äôs‚Äù every day, every week, every month, compounding into year‚Äôs it will
change your whole life. ‚ÄúTrust me‚Äù 
Although I do not win every single day, I try my hardest to keep stacking them up üíØ.
-
Using this formula has got me to where I am today. Every single day I create a ‚ÄúPOWER‚Äù list and execute it! The list could be handwritten or digitally stored. My power list contains five essential items I must complete daily, and anything else I get done is a bonus. Completing this POWER list daily = a W. If I do not complete the items on the POWER list, there is no W.
E.g. 
-
POWER
* Post
* Finish onboarding call
* Work on speech
* Client call
* Partner call
-
I have been doing this for years now, and it has helped me to stay on track. Staying accountable to get that W every day stops me from slipping.
-
I regularly compare what my life looked like five years ago to now. I did not care about a W. My life consisted of gangs, drugs, alcohol, self-sabotage, crime, and bad mental health, none of which will get me a ‚ÄúW‚Äù.
-
IT ALL STARTS WITH YOUR DAILY ACTIONS. 
-
You will not catch me SLIPPING any more. Who else is STACKING them W‚Äôs? üëëüî•üòé
-

This comes after previous reductions to $26.5 million and $23.95 million, as real estate activity picks up in Brentwood.

Carrey, who skyrocketed to fame with roles in movies like ‚ÄúThe Mask‚Äù and ‚ÄúDumb & Dumber,‚Äù bought the nearly 11,000-square-foot ranch-style home in 1994 for $3.8 million. The property is filled with features like French doors, a yoga and meditation area, a pool with a waterfall, and an art deco theater. Outside, there are beautiful gardens, a tennis court, and a large patio. Inside, there are unique touches like mohair-covered walls, wood pillars, and multiple fireplaces. Caption:
Who usually attends your festivals? 

Solo guests? families? Large groups? Men? Women?

Absolutely all of the above and everything in between, we have a big emphasis on being family friendly hence we are inviting Kids for free. We also have some groups coming that have chosen our festival as a meet up and are creating their own little lounge area for their community. If you are differently-abled then you can bring your carer for free. We aim to be as inclusive as possible and make everyone‚Äôs stay as comfortable as we can. There are two different glamping options to suit as many needs as possible in the form of family friendly glamping yurts and a particularly funky glamoing Bus called ‚ÄòScarangar‚Äô which takes care of all your needs during the festival in VIP style. Regular camping is free of course and live in vehicles are welcome.There are lots of people who fly solo at our events as they say they meet more people when they come alone, some say they prefer it as it forces them to be sociable and make the most of the incredible well-being offerings and epic musicians. We are all one big happy family, so by the end of the weekend we hope that‚Äôs how everyone will feel. This is one of the benefits of it being a smaller and more intimate gig than some of the bigger events.

Caption:
Welcome to Mindfulness Monday! Think about how these tips can help you be successful.

1) Set boundaries and respect others: this creates safe and condusive relationships, create mutual kindness with everyone.

2) Allow yourself to try new things: remember that creativity and new experiences can foster new connections and allow you to expand your horizons. Don‚Äôt hold yourself back!

3) Love yourself and embrace failure: always remember that mistakes are stepping stones to further success, so never be discouraged!

Caption:
"In the Qabalah, the Serpent of Wisdom refers to the direction or course of the Hebrew letters as placed on the twenty-two Tarot paths of the Thirty-Two Paths of Wisdom. Together, these paths form a symbol‚Äîthe Serpent of Wisdom. Therefore, the Tarot paths equal the Serpent of Wisdom while the Sephiroth equal the Path of the Flaming Sword. As the Path of the Flaming Sword represents Creation descending from the highest to the lowest (Kether to Malkuth), the Serpent of Wisdom climbs the Tree of Life from the lowest path (Tav) to the highest path (Aleph). You can see now how the symbology of the Serpent is present within the Qabalah and the Tree of Life. It is the Kundalini energy that lights up the entire Tree of Life when awakened. It is the Serpent that tempted Eve to eat of the Tree of Knowledge of Good and Evil in the Garden of Eden, even though God strictly forbade this. Through their disobedience to God, Adam and Eve were banished out of the Garden. Now, it is this Serpent again through whom we are to return to the Garden of Eden. We do so by awakening the Kundalini, the process of which is synonymous with activating and invigorating the entire Tree of Life and travelling upwards in consciousness. We ascend the Tree of Life in succession upwards, starting with the lowest Sephira, Malkuth, and ending with the highest Sephira, Kether." -Excerpt from "The Magus: Kundalini and the Golden Dawn" by Neven Paar

Caption:
There have been a couple of people messaging me with their disagreeing opinions on my post about being free of the opinion of others. Their opinion justifies why others make them angry. 

When somebody makes us angry, the only reason we actually get angry is because we are attached to how others should think and behave toward us. To think this is to be in denial of what is. As we become more conscious, we see the clinging of our own minds (Upadana), which creates our own suffering. 

When we get angry or even disappointed, look at the way we think, and we will see the clinging of our mind, which creates our state of mind, our depression or anxiety, etc. 

To change the concepts of what we are clinging to, is to allow others to think, have opinions, and act as themselves, which is to accept what just is.

The foundation of being free of suffering boils down to four key points to live by.
Acceptance 
Appreciation 
Non Judgement 
No Attachment 

Anandam üôè (bliss be with you)
Satya Das

Caption:
Happy Monday! What better way to start the week than a provider shoutout? Today we are highlighting Krissy Zechmann, LICSW. 

For the past 17 years, Krissy has enjoyed working with individuals and families in a variety of social work and mental health settings. Her previous experience includes outpatient mental health therapy, child welfare services, hospice social work, and most recently, school based mental health serving within Millard Public Schools District.

Krissy has expertise in assisting individuals and families in management of symptoms related to anxiety, depression, mood disorders, behavioral issues, environmental stressors, and major life changes. She enjoys working with adolescents and adults while providing individualized treatment to all patients.
‚Äã
Further, she brings a wealth of knowledge and experience working with people who are faced with difficult end of life related issues.  She understands grief and loss and is passionate about walking with those who are terminally ill and those who have a loved one who is nearing the end stages of life. Krissy knows that loss comes in many forms over a lifetime and encourages those who are struggling to seek support.

Krissy understands that the development of trust and rapport is crucial in the therapy process. She believes that everyone deserves dignity and respect and she strives to provide that to every person she works with. Her goal in therapy is guide those in the healing process while teaching effective ways to manage symptoms, stressors, and conflicts in life. 

Krissy is currently accepting new patients. Give us a call today to learn more! (402) 614-0010

3. Det vigtigste har m√•ske v√¶ret villigheden til at udvikle og l√¶re af hinandens forskelligheder‚Ä¶(jeg tror ikke man kan v√¶re ret meget mere forskellig end min mand og jeg)‚Ä¶
Villighed til at l√¶re at elske p√• andre m√•der end det som var os naturligt - str√¶kke sig efter at forst√• og se den andens perspektiv - det har forandret mange konflikter og frustrationer til berigende samtaler‚Ä¶

S√• nej det har ikke v√¶ret rosenr√∏dt i 18 √•r - det ER og har v√¶ret en vandring i livet med alt hvad det indeb√¶rer af ups and downs‚Ä¶

Det fylder mig med dyb taknemmelighed at et andet menneske kender mig helt ind og stadig elsker mig‚Ä¶

Mit h√•b er at vi m√• blive ved med b√•de at elske og lade os elske‚Ä¶.‚Äùk√¶rlighed er ikke en f√∏lelse‚Äù som den gode @amandalagoni s√• fint skriver i bogen af samme titel - og som jeg i√∏vrigt anbefaler hvis du endnu ikke har l√¶st den‚Ä¶

Caption:
Increasing the awareness of men‚Äôs mental health can lead to individuals and families helping men identify the root causes of mental health issues. In addition to increasing the likelihood of helping a loved one overcome challenges during a difficult time

There is no difference between the mental health conditions experienced by Black, Indigenous, and People of Color men and those experienced by white men, although BIPOC men have a lower level of mental health care access.

In spite of the importance of Men‚Äôs Mental Health Awareness Month, we must take into account men‚Äôs mental health all year long. Men are more accepting of expressing their emotions and seeking help than they used to be, but we should still address the continuing stigma that men should not seek mental health treatment.

Caption:
As we age, our #experiences #influence our thoughts and behaviors. Remember, it‚Äôs never too late to change your #mindset for increased #happiness and fulfillment. This change doesn‚Äôt happen overnight, but with daily intentions and consistent actions, you can start to adopt healthier ways of thinking and being.

Start by cultivating a growth mindset, viewing challenges as #opportunities for personal development. Believe in your #potential to #learn and grow, regardless of your age. Regularly practice #gratitude by acknowledging the #positives in your life, which can significantly #boost your mood and outlook.

Engage in lifelong learning to keep your mind active. Whether it‚Äôs learning new skills, picking up new hobbies, or #exploring new subjects, these activities open up new avenues for joy and fulfillment.

Incorporate #mindfulness into your #daily routine. A few minutes of #meditation each day can reduce stress, increase self-awareness, and promote a sense of peace. Surround yourself with people who #uplift and #inspire you, as positive social #connections are crucial for emotional health.

Identify what truly matters to you and set achievable goals. Working towards something you‚Äôre #passionate about brings a sense of purpose and satisfaction. Remember, regular #exercise benefits both your #body and #mind by reducing anxiety and depression, enhancing mood, and improving cognitive function.

Release #negativethoughts and past regrets by focusing on the #present and future. Sometimes, seeking guidance from a therapist or coach can help you reshape your mindset and overcome #mental barriers.

Reprogramming your mind is an ongoing journey. By setting daily intentions and taking consistent actions, you can unlock new levels of joy and satisfaction at any stage of life. üíôüßø Just remember to always out yourself first because you are worthy! ‚ú®üôè

Caption:
So pleased to have the beautiful Emily Cobie and Friends join us for the Elemental Temple celebrations this year. Emily Cobie is a student of Bhakti Yoga, the practice of devotional yoga. Her mission is to share the power of Mantra and chanting, mainly through Kirtan, as a way to connect to divinity and collective consciousness.
 
She began learning Mantra 8 years ago with her Teacher Ajay Kumar through Vedic Chanting in his Shala, Shtalam 8 -Ashtanga & Vedanta Centre. Since then, Emily has been inspired and honoured to be a student of Sheela Bringi, a devotional Indian and Raga singer. She has also learnt from Kirtan leaders such as Sivani Mata and Ahisha Dasi. After spending time with Radhika Das and Friends in the holy place, Vrindavan, Emily has spent the last year sharing Kirtan in Buckinghamshire and numerous festivals and events in the UK. Emily holds a monthly Kirtan in Marlow as part of the Oh Shala Festival.
 
My core values lie in a practice of love, kindness, compassion and service in community. Through the medium of Kirtan we can call on divinity to open our hearts as we chant and sing together, weaving magic and collective healing.
@emily.cobie

Caption:
The reason I teach yoga is the same reason I practice it: It breathes life into the unfelt and speaks quietly to hidden truths until the subtle becomes so profound you‚Äôre transformed completely. 

As a teacher I aim to offer you time and space to explore yourself beneath the surface of daily life. Who are you beneath the waves? As you begin investigating the root of your wholeness life becomes less about performance. And that is real liberation. 
But for many of us, looking into the mirror and digging around into the truth of who we are requires guidance and some assistance to keep us courageous and keep us honest. Every single time I get the opportunity to stand in front of a class my only hope is that I breathe encouragement into you to find the strength to live inside your worth. 

You are an ocean: timeless, pure, and whole. Much of life cannot be explained, it can only be witnessed. So until you get to the place of witnessing the amazement of your being, I‚Äôm here to observe and write the love letters for you.

Caption:
Why Should I Meditate?

Stress. That‚Äôs why.

The latest statistics indicate 74% of adults in the UK are stressed, and is it any wonder after the last few years?  The impact of this statistic means that both our mental and physical health is being adversely affected.

The effects of long-term stress put our overall health at risk. 

To cope, some people turn to food to self-medicate, gaining weight, leading to a new set of health problems. 60% of UK adults medicate through alcohol.  And whilst a social gin is perfectly acceptable, there can be a time with alcohol when the fun stops. 

Stress can also bring with it a whole array of mental health problems including anxiety and depression. 

As a nation, we are getting sicker. Managing your stress levels is crucial for improving your overall wellbeing.

Lowering stress levels will enhance your focus on tasks, improving productivity whether at work or home. 

Your emotional health improves with lower stress, fostering a positive outlook and emotional stability.

It can also improve your sleep hygiene; a better night‚Äôs sleep means everything feels better.  You will have more energy to tackle the day. 

It will also lower blood pressure levels and boost your immune system.

I work with busy people who are looking for ways to boost resilience and manage their stress so that they don‚Äôt always feel as if they are on the back foot with life.

Using a range of techniques, I work with you to develop a self-care routine that fits in with your lifestyle to lower stress levels without the woo. 

Want to know more? 

Drop me a message and let‚Äôs chat.

Caption:
üåü Today, let's discuss fasting as a spiritual practice. üåü‚Å†
‚Å†
Long fasting refers to fasting periods beyond 24 hours, often 48-hour or even 72-hour fasts. While typically seen for its physical benefits, fasting also offers significant emotional and psychological advantages.‚Å†
‚Å†
üåø Mental Clarity and Focus: Many report enhanced mental clarity and focus during fasting due to stable energy from increased ketone production.‚Å†
‚Å†
üåø Increased Resilience: Fasting helps develop emotional resilience. Overcoming hunger teaches coping with discomfort in other life areas, improving stress management and challenge-facing abilities.‚Å†
‚Å†
üåø Mood Improvement: Fasting boosts mood by stimulating serotonin production, which regulates mood, happiness, and anxiety. It also increases brain-derived neurotrophic factor (BDNF), crucial for mental health.‚Å†
‚Å†
üåø Sense of Achievement and Control: Completing fasting periods provides a sense of achievement and empowerment, boosting self-esteem and confidence in managing eating habits and health.‚Å†
‚Å†
üåø Spiritual and Emotional Reflection: Integrated in many spiritual practices, fasting allows for introspection and meditation, leading to a deeper connection with thoughts and emotions, fostering peace and purpose.‚Å†
‚Å†
üåø Reduction in Anxiety: Fasting regulates hormonal balance, reduces anxiety, and stabilizes energy levels, helping manage nervousness linked to blood sugar fluctuations.‚Å†
‚Å†
üåø Detoxification and Emotional Cleansing: Physical detoxification during fasting often leads to a sense of emotional cleansing, resulting in improved emotional well-being.‚Å†
‚Å†
When done correctly and safely, fasting can enhance both physical and emotional wellness. Approach fasting mindfully and ideally under the guidance of a healthcare professional to ensure safety and effectiveness.‚Å†
‚Å†

Caption:
Self-Reflection: What Are Your Negative Thoughts Trying to Protect You From?

Negative thoughts can be frustrating, but they are not random. They serve a purpose, often trying to protect you from something‚Äîwhether it‚Äôs experiencing pain again, suffering, or failure.
Understanding the root of these thoughts can transform them into a more empowering self-narrative. Here are some examples:

- If you fear failure, your negative thoughts might be trying to protect you from the disappointment and self-doubt that comes with it.
- If you avoid new relationships, your negative thoughts might shield you from potential heartbreak or rejection.
- If you doubt your abilities, your negative thoughts might be protecting you from the risk of making mistakes and facing criticism.

Once you identify what your negative thoughts are trying to protect you from, you can reframe them. Choose a way to protect yourself that is not limiting but empowering.

For instance:
- Instead of avoiding failure, embrace challenges as opportunities to learn and grow.
- Instead of fearing new relationships, view them as chances to connect and enrich your life.
- Instead of doubting your abilities, trust in your capacity to improve and succeed.

Change your narrative and find ways to feel safe without holding yourself back. You deserve a life free from the constraints of old, limiting beliefs.

Caption:
Self-Reflection: What Are Your Negative Thoughts Trying to Protect You From?

Negative thoughts can be frustrating, but they are not random. They serve a purpose, often trying to protect you from something‚Äîwhether it's experiencing pain again, suffering, or failure.
Understanding the root of these thoughts can transform them into a more empowering self-narrative. Here are some examples:

- If you fear failure, your negative thoughts might be trying to protect you from the disappointment and self-doubt that comes with it.
- If you avoid new relationships, your negative thoughts might shield you from potential heartbreak or rejection.
- If you doubt your abilities, your negative thoughts might be protecting you from the risk of making mistakes and facing criticism.

Once you identify what your negative thoughts are trying to protect you from, you can reframe them. Choose a way to protect yourself that is not limiting but empowering.

For instance:
- Instead of avoiding failure, embrace challenges as opportunities to learn and grow.
- Instead of fearing new relationships, view them as chances to connect and enrich your life.
- Instead of doubting your abilities, trust in your capacity to improve and succeed.

Change your narrative and find ways to feel safe without holding yourself back. You deserve a life free from the constraints of old, limiting beliefs.

Caption:
Did you know one of our star colors comes from beets? They're known for their numerous health benefits, but the skin! The skin benefits are skin-ning! Fluency's got you for your healthy goals. 

üåü Rich in Antioxidants: Beets are packed with antioxidants, particularly betalains, which help fight free radicals and reduce oxidative stress, preventing premature aging and maintaining youthful skin.
üåü Anti-Inflammatory Properties: The anti-inflammatory compounds in beets can help soothe irritated skin, reducing redness and inflammation.
üåü Vitamin C Content: Beets are a good source of vitamin C, which aids in collagen production, helping to keep the skin firm and reducing wrinkles.
üåü Detoxification: Beets help detoxify the body, which in turn can lead to clearer skin by eliminating toxins that can cause breakouts and other skin issues.
üåü Improved Circulation: The nitrates in beets improve blood flow and circulation, providing better oxygen and nutrient delivery to skin cells, resulting in a healthier complexion.
üåü Hydration: Beets have a high water content, which helps keep the skin hydrated, improving its overall texture and appearance.
üåü Natural Skin Lightening: Beets can help lighten dark spots and even out skin tone due to their ability to improve blood flow and detoxify the skin.
üåü Acne Prevention: The anti-inflammatory and detoxifying properties of beets can help prevent acne by keeping pores clear and reducing inflammation.
üåü Healing Properties: Beets contain essential nutrients like folate and iron, which support skin repair and regeneration, aiding in the healing of scars and blemishes.

Caption:
BEYOND ACCEPTING OR REJECTING 

The open path is a matter of working purely with what is, of giving up altogether the fear that something may not work, that something may end in failure. One has to give up the paranoia that one might not fit into situations, that one might be rejected. One purely deals with life as it is.

Ch√∂gyam Trungpa "Cutting Through Spiritual Materialism" 

You do not have to abandon worldly activities in order to attain effortless unconcern. You should know that worldly activities and effortless unconcern are not two different things, but if you keep thinking about rejection and grasping, you make them two.

HuiNeng (the 6th Zen Patriarch), translation by Thomas Cleary, Classics of Buddhism and Zen, Volume 1 

The next time you lose heart and you can‚Äôt bear to experience what you‚Äôre feeling, you might recall this instruction: change the way you see it and lean in. Instead of blaming our discomfort on outer circumstances or on our own weakness, we can choose to stay present and awake to our experience, not rejecting it, not grasping it, not buying the stories that we relentlessly tell ourselves. This is priceless advice that addresses the true cause of suffering ‚Äî yours, mine, and that of all living beings.

Pema Ch√∂dron, "Taking the Leap: Freeing Ourselves from Old Habits and Fears"

The Way is perfect like vast space
where nothing is lacking and nothing is in excess.
Indeed, it is due to our choosing to accept or reject
that we do not see the true nature of things.
Be serene in the oneness of things
and such erroneous views will disappear by themselves.

Sengcan (Third Zen Patriarch), Trans. Richard B. Clarke 

Since everything is but an apparition,
Perfect in being what it is,
Having nothing to do with good and bad,
Acceptance or rejection,
You might as well burst out laughing!

Longchenpa, Glimpse After Glimpse: Daily Reflections on Living and Dying"

Caption:
Foundations in Teaching Mindfulness Meditation - starts 3rd July @michaelstoneteaching 

‚ÄúOur lives happen in the present moment. Often we are preoccupied and distracted, and we don‚Äôt have the skills for inhabiting the body in a way that‚Äôs safe, still, and calm.‚Äù Michael Stone

The 9 week course developed and delivered by the late Michael Stone, will provide insights into the art and science of mindfulness. It is designed both for people interested in maturing and developing a personal practice and as a foundation to offering mindfulness-based interventions to others in a class-based setting.

The course is linear and structured in its approach, allowing students to explore their own personal journey on a week by week basis, with guided videos from Michael, readings and audio practices to help build a base of both knowledge and experience. Students will have one week to complete the requirements for each module before being able to move on to the next module as a way to ensure that the whole group begins and ends the training at the same time.

"This has been a very enlightening and enjoyable experience. I found the Mindfulness Practice Teaching exercises confidence building for my teaching, and I loved the range of techniques and detail of the audios and video excerpts. The content progressed in a digestible and logical way as we moved though the course. I particularly enjoyed the chance to reflect and submit to the group discussion points and share experiences with each other on the course. I leave with a deeper understanding of meditation and how to offer these valuable practices to others".

Olivia Marquis, Remembering Michael Stone: Foundations in Teaching Mindfulness Meditation Training

Caption:
In this collection (as well as a lot of my previous work), I deface the painting as a way to make fun of the seriousness of the portrait. It's my sarcastic sense of humour trying to make sense ‚Äì to laugh because otherwise we might cry ‚Äì about the absurdity of life and the experiences so many of us face.

Every person who has sat for me has a story to tell. A story often with a lot of love and joy, juxtaposed with heartache, or health worries or financial problems: their perceived failures.

From infertility to mental health challenges, so many of these are shared by us all. The more I work and meet women the more I see the invisible thread that connects us all. We are so bound together and have so much that unites us beyond our age, career or marital status. And I'm just trying to tell part of that story.

Caption:
Dear Dharma Friends,
Thank you for your continued support and understanding of the dissemination effort of Soto Zen School.
This is 3rd time post regarding Noto peninsula in Ishikawa relief fund.
We extend our prays for the victims and their families and wish for their early recovery and restoration of life.
We appreciate it if you could kindly send checks to the Association of Soto Zen Buddhists so that we can transfer the amount to the Soto shu shumu-cho, Soto Zen Buddhism administrative headquarters office in Japan.
More than 100 Soto Zen temples affected by the disaster. We are sharing the photos of some temples.

Caption:
‚ú® healing era ‚ú® series 

A little post all about how to heal the physical body. These are just little tips from me, someone who has had to work tirelessly to heal my body, love my body and come home to my body again. 

So my 5 tips to connect again with your body - 

‚ú® in every way possible, become friends with yourself. With your physical body. Find acceptance in who you are at your essence, this means not being a certain person or acting a particular way to make others happy. 

‚ú® nourish your body. Give yourself the energy you deserve! If you want chocolate cake, eat it. Do not beat yourself up over wanting to eat things you enjoy. Equally, finding healthy, nourishing and fulfilling foods will also give you a lot of joy (and keep you going for longer)! 

‚ú® pamper your body. Buy the expensive body lotion, just once. Your body is a temple and it needs to be shown love with physical touch. By massaging yourself in that lovely smelly lotion, washing your body and looking after your body, you are showing yourself you are capable of lovely things. 

‚ú® moving the body. I don‚Äôt mean a full hit workout every 2 days (unless that works for you!) I mean intentionally movement. Yoga, slow walks, hikes, dog walks, Pilates, somatic workouts. All of these exercises help you to connect to your body. They aren‚Äôt scary. Most can be found on YouTube or at a local gym class - or they are free in nature! 

‚ú® grounding. This works across the board for healing. Allow yourself to feel deeply connected to something other than the overwhelming thoughts in your head. Teach your body it is safe and out of flight / fight. You can do this by sitting on the ground, feeling the ground beneath you, feeling the floor, the earth and the roots of the soil. Visualise this until you feel calmer and relaxed. 

Also, do we like the new colour change!? üòÉ

Caption: "Nonfabrication is a state of shamatha meditation that is free from any conceptual labeling. At this stage, there is no process of labeling our experience as one thing or another, such as thoughts of "resting" or "not resting" or "This is Mahamudra shamatha" or "This is not Mahamudra shamatha." We must be totally free from these fabrications. When we rest in that state of mind, there is a great sense of freedom."\n-Dzogchen Ponlop Rinpoche | June 7th | https://bit.ly/nsi24mmm

Caption:
What does it mean to be free
Led by Jack Petranker

September 24-29, 2024
Annual Time Space Knowledge Retreat in Germany 

We live our lives within limits we have learned to take for granted.

Because we put our own wants and needs at the center of experience, we live in a world where time rushes on from moment to moment, separating us from what we desire.

Because we are always reaching out for what we hope to possess, we occupy a small and close-off space. We rob ourselves of the joy of being fully present.

In this retreat, we will question the limits we impose on ourselves and the positions we impose on experience. We will learn how to connect with all that happens, and to appreciate more fully the beauty of the world we inhabit.

To register check the link in our bio.
